sec.p:
We conducted a series of independent t tests to examine whether measures of perceived relevance and efficacy differed as a function of occupation type (training director vs. non–training director; see Table 2
) and program focus (clinical vs. nonclinical or research; see Table 3
). Compared to training directors, faculty were more likely to view a publication in the journal as beneficial for obtaining a position at a postgraduate school, t(26) = 2.53, p < .05, d = 0.99. In addition, respondents from clinical programs perceived publishing in graduate school journals as more beneficial for obtaining postgraduate school positions, t(30) = 2.84, p < .01, d = 1.03, and experience with graduate student journals as relevant for training, t(24) = 2.05, p = .05, d = 0.84, and able to facilitate interest in research, t(26) = 2.53, p < .05, d = 0.99. The degrees of freedom for each t test differ because of missing data, as not all respondents answered every question.
